      "id":"education/2013/oct/17/teachers-strike-unions-claim-success-schools-close",
      "sectionId":"education",
      "sectionName":"Education",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T12:39:49Z",
      "webTitle":"Teachers' strike: unions claim success as hundreds of schools close",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/oct/17/teachers-strike-unions-claim-success-schools-close",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/education/2013/oct/17/teachers-strike-unions-claim-success-schools-close",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"NASUWT says latest one-day strike has support from parents and public, while DfE disputes scale of disruption",
        "headline":"Teachers' strike: unions claim success as hundreds of schools close",
        "body":"<p>Teaching unions have claimed significant success from the latest in a series of one-day strikes over pay, pension and working conditions, with many hundreds of schools completely or partly closed across London and the south-east as well as the north-east and south-west of England.</p><p>However, the Department for Education disputed the scale of the disruption, saying its figures suggested only 27% of schools in affected regions were entirely shut.</p><p>The NASUWT, which is organising the walkout along with the other main teachers' union, the NUT, said the strike had gained significant support and caused major disruption. Teachers in the east of England, the Midlands and Yorkshire and Humberside walked out on 1 October, and there will be a national one-day strike later this year, part of a bitter and increasingly personal confrontation with the education secretary, Michael Gove.</p><p>The unions have held public rallies in Durham, Bristol and London to coincide with the strikes. An NASUWT spokeswoman said around 2,000 people marched in Durham, and had enjoyed significant support from passersby: \"When we marched through the city centre we got cheered and clapped all the way. It seems like we've got a lot of parental support and public support.\"</p><p>The union did not have a figure for the school closures, but the spokeswoman said it appeared significant: \"We haven't got any numbers or percentages, but the overwhelming majority of members have joined the strike action, and most schools are either closed, partially closed or affected in some way.\"</p><p>Details from local authorities and newspapers have suggested significant disruption. A list of schools in the Newcastle Chronicle showed the majority closed or partially open. <a href=\"http://www.standard.co.uk/news/education/schools-strike-chaos-forces-parents-to-take-the-day-off-to-look-after-children-sent-home-8886282.html\" title=\"\">Reports from London</a> suggested the worst-affected local authorities saw up to 90% of schools affected, with only <a href=\"http://www.hounslow.gov.uk/index/education_and_learning/schools_and_colleges/strike.htm\" title=\"\">eight out of 70 fully open in Hounslow</a> and seven of 75 fully open in Redbridge.</p><p>The picture in the south-west was more mixed. Cornwall council <a href=\"http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Parents-face-disruptions-teacher-strikes-hit/story-19948865-detail/story.html#axzz2hydOqQCD\" title=\"\">has given a tally</a> of 107 out of 272 schools affected. Devon council <a href=\"http://www.devonschoolclosures.info/\" title=\"\">listed several dozen closed or part-closed schools</a>, with a <a href=\"http://www.somerset.gov.uk/irj/public/news/directory/articles?rid=/guid/f0bac483-b346-3010-3d8a-ebe00c417eab\" title=\"\">similar situation in Somerset</a>.</p><p>In Kent, meanwhile, <a href=\"http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/Teachers-strike-October-17-List-Kent-schools/story-19940660-detail/story.html#axzz2hyiVc5aS\" title=\"\">36 schools were entirely shut for the day with another 67 not fully open</a>.</p><p>A DfE statement said its figures, based on a tally of relevant local authorities, said 27% of schools were entirely closed. A DfE spokeswoman called the strike \"disappointing\", saying all it did was disrupt parents' lives, harm education and \"damage the reputation of the profession\".</p><p>The unions argue they have been pushed into strike action because the DfE, and particularly Gove, have refused to properly negotiate over changes to pay, working conditions and pensions, notably the planned introduction of performance-related pay and an end to automatic incremental pay rises. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/sep/05/teachers-england-strike-pay-pensions\" title=\"\">Announcing the strike plan last month</a>, the general secretary of NASUWT, Chris Keates, said the responsibility lay \"entirely with the secretary of state\".</p><p>The DfE argues that the majority of parents support performance-related pay and don't want teachers to walk out.</p><p>Gove is in the US this week. The junior education minister, David Laws, called the strike \"bad for pupils and bad for parents\". He said: \"I don't believe this strike is justified and it is not going to change government policy.\"</p><p>Speaking on ITV's Daybreak, Laws said: \"These are reforms that are taking place across the whole of the public sector. They are, I'm afraid, necessary in these very difficult times where we have to get the budget back under control. Most teachers, I believe, accept that.</p><p>\"The right way to fix education policy is either by talking with the government or through the ballot box, and not taking industrial action. I think that is the view of the vast majority of teachers who I don't think will be striking today even in those areas where the NUT and NASUWT are trying to take action.\"</p><p>Keates said teachers were dedicated and \"do not take strike action lightly\". She added: \"No teacher has any wish to inconvenience parents or disrupt pupils' education, but this action is not the failure or  unreasonableness of teachers. It is the failure and unreasonableness of the secretary of state, who day in, day out is disrupting the education of children and young people through his attacks on the teaching profession.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420254629|2013-10-17T14:03:15Z|4651ca5e00e426ba6c02ee7cf17d55b286701681 -->",
