      "id":"society/2013/oct/17/social-mobility-tsar-work-route-poverty",
      "sectionId":"society",
      "sectionName":"Society",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T13:42:35Z",
      "webTitle":"Social mobility tsar says work is no longer clear route out of poverty",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/oct/17/social-mobility-tsar-work-route-poverty",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/society/2013/oct/17/social-mobility-tsar-work-route-poverty",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Alan Milburn report argues much of UK is caught in poverty trap forged from low pay, poor skills and falling value of tax credits",
        "headline":"Social mobility tsar says work is no longer clear route out of poverty",
        "body":"<p>Work is no longer a clear route of poverty because of excessive low pay, the falling value of tax credits and lack of workforce skills, Alan Milburn has said, launching a landmark state-of-the-nation report as chair of the government's social mobility and child poverty commission.</p><p></p><p>He called for a higher minimum wage set differently in different sectors, and an end to perks for wealthier pensioners such as the winter fuel allowance, pointing out that pensioners had been relatively cocooned from the impact of austerity.</p><p></p><p>In a vast array of proposals across a 250-page report, the commission also calls for more performance-related pay for teachers and a requirement that free schools have an explicit objective of narrowing education attainment gaps, and urges ministers to drop \"the strivers versus shirkers rhetoric\", which it says undermines support for welfare spending.</p><p></p><p>It says the Department for Education needs to focus not just on low-income children but low-attainment children, pointing out that concern about the quality of teaching is gradually shifting from London to leafier areas such as west Berkshire and Bournemouth.</p><p></p><p></p><p>The report, delayed because of party conferences, is likely to be mined by all three parties for ideas for their party manifestos. Overall it finds the government is not doing enough to change the dial on poverty and social mobility given the strong headwinds that are stagnating incomes, and increasing inequality.</p><p></p><p>Overall, the report finds the impact of the government's cuts programme has been regressive, with the bottom 20% in society making a bigger contribution than all but the top 20%.</p><p></p><p>The report adds that the cuts programme has been intergenerationally unfair. It finds pensioners have been protected, but families with children (32% of working-age families) have borne half the cost of tax and benefit changes and almost two-thirds of spending cuts.</p><p></p><p>Milburn said he agreed with the deputy prime minister, <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nick-clegg/10384339/The-Coalition-is-improving-peoples-lives-but-we-know-the-jobs-not-finished-yet.html\" title=\"\">Nick Clegg, who wrote in the Telegraph before the report was released that it would be wrong as a result to punish pensioners</a>. But Milburn said: \"The right question to ask is whether in this time when families are under pressure, where people who are working are facing a squeeze on their benefits and public services, and when the poorest people are having their benefits capped, is it right that pensioners are having their benefits not just protected, but enhanced?\"</p><p></p><p>He urged the parties to look at the winter fuel allowance, adding: \"I have not met a politician in private who does not agree with that sentiment. The question is whether they are prepared to say what they say in private in public and more importantly to act in a way which is consistent with their private views.\"</p><p></p><p>Setting out how pensioners are benefiting in this parliament, the commission says state pension costs are going up by 17.5% during the course of the parliament – £13bn in 2013-14 prices – a sum equivalent to more than half of the savings from welfare reforms planned for 2014-15.</p><p></p><p>The report also warns that many of today's children face the prospect of having lower living standards than their parents when they grow up. He says the trend of wages stagnating is not a blip but a trajectory that has been with the country for 10 years.</p><p></p><p>The trend is creating growing insecurity among average-income families, not just lower-income families. \"Material disadvantage is more pronounced at the bottom of society but is far more widespread than people imagine,\" he says.</p><p></p><p>\"When combined with rising house prices, university fees and youth unemployment, these factors may have induced a sense of fear among many average-income families' parents that their children will be worse off than they were.</p><p></p><p>\"There is precious little sign of a decade-long trend of bottom-half stagnating in terms of earnings coming to an end.\"</p><p></p><p>The report warns: \"If, as seems likely, the recovery sees the trend of the last decade continuing – where the top part of the society prospers and the bottom half stagnates – inequalities will grow and the rungs of the social ladder will grow further apart.</p><p></p><p>\"We see a danger that social mobility, having risen in the middle of the last century then flatlined in the end, could go into reverse in the first part of this century.\"</p><p></p><p>In remarks that are likely to lead to a row with business leaders, Milburn says employers will need to pay staff more and provide more training. He argues that in an age of austerity there is little likelihood that tax credits will rise greatly in the future, and more of the burden of lifting people out of poverty must lie with higher wages. \"There has to be a fairer sharing of the burden between what the taxpayer does and what the employer does.\"</p><p></p><p>The commission says \"two-thirds of Britain's poor children are now in families where an adult works; this compared with less than half in 1997. The principal problem is those working parents simply do not earn enough to escape poverty.\"</p><p></p><p>The report calls for the Low Pay Commission to be given a wider remit, adding: \"The UK has now one of the highest rates of low pay in the developed world. The national minimum wage is now worth £1,000 less in real terms than it was in 2008.</p><p></p><p>\"Today 4.8 million workers earn less than the living wage, worth £7.45 an hour outside London. Too often the working poor are the forgotten people of Britain. A comprehensive approach to tackling in-work poverty is the missing piece of the government's policy jigsaw.\"</p><p></p><p>Milburn himself suggested that the minimum wage could be set sectorally, arguing that industries such as finance and construction could afford to pay more than the current minimum wage.</p><p></p><p>The report recommends that half of all firms should offer apprenticeships, instead of the current 30%.</p><p></p><p>It also suggests the government should renew its drive to eliminate long-term youth unemployment, saying the coalition's programme the Youth Contract has failed.</p><p></p><p>The commission calls for the government to reallocate funding for childcare from higher-rate taxpayers to help those on universal credit meet more of their childcare costs. It points out that in the 2013 budget 80% of the new funding for childcare will go to households in the top half of the income distribution.</p><p></p><p>On child poverty, the commission finds that the UK has gone from having one of the highest levels in Europe to a rate near the average over the past 15 years. It says the numbers of children in relative poverty have fallen recently but those in absolute poverty increased by more than 275,000 in 2011-12.</p><p></p><p>Milburn added: \"[The] ambition to end child poverty that the previous government set is going to be missed by a considerable margin, possibly by as much as 2 million children in relative poverty.\"</p><p></p><p>More broadly the report argues that social elites have not opened up, whether at the top universities or top professions. \"In particular top universities have not progressed as far as universities as a whole.\" But it also finds that tuition fees have not deterred poorer students, but have put off poorer mature students.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420259791|2013-10-17T14:03:15Z|bbd192b182ff7c05cedee3c88461fd7648b1ef6f -->",
