      "id":"politics/2013/oct/17/plebgate-mitchell-pretty-sore-treatment-clegg",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T10:14:37Z",
      "webTitle":"Plebgate: Mitchell right to feel 'pretty sore' about police treatment, says Clegg",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/17/plebgate-mitchell-pretty-sore-treatment-clegg",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/oct/17/plebgate-mitchell-pretty-sore-treatment-clegg",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Deputy PM joins ranks of ministers calling for action against officers accused of giving false account of meeting with Mitchell",
        "headline":"Plebgate: Mitchell right to feel 'pretty sore' about police treatment, says Clegg",
        "body":"<p>Nick Clegg has said that Andrew Mitchell is right to feel \"pretty sore\" about his treatment at the hands of three police officers who called for him to resign as chief whip last year after allegedly providing a false account of a meeting.</p><p></p><p>The deputy prime minister backed the home secretary, Theresa May, who called for disciplinary action against the representatives of the Police Federation who met Mitchell a month after an altercation with armed officers in Downing Street in September last year.</p><p></p><p>Clegg spoke out after the Independent Police Complaints Commission questioned the behaviour of three representatives of the federation from Warwickshire, West Mercia and West Midlands – Inspector Ken MacKaill, Detective Sergeant Stuart Hinton and Sergeant Chris Jones – who called on him to resign as chief whip after a meeting in his Sutton Coldfield constituency in October last year.</p><p></p><p>The officers issued their statement on the grounds that Mitchell had failed to give a full account of the Downing Street incident in which he allegedly called an armed officer a \"fucking pleb\" after he refused to allow the then chief whip to wheel his bikes through the gates.</p><p></p><p>But in the IPCC's own report into the incident, issued on Tuesday, the police watchdog called for a panel to determine whether the officers had given a false account after a transcript showed that Mitchell had outlined in some detail the circumstances of the Downing Street incident. Mitchell had told the federation representatives that he had sworn in the presence of the armed officers in Downing Street but had not described them as plebs.</p><p></p><p>Speaking on his weekly phone-in show on LBC radio, Clegg said the IPCC report raised questions about the behaviour of the Police Federation representatives at the meeting.</p><p></p><p>The deputy prime minister said: \"They came straight out of that meeting and claimed that he had not provided them with his side of the story when the subsequent revelation that the meeting had been recorded shows that he made every attempt to try and explain what happened. He said he didn't use the pleb word but he did have an outburst and he apologised for it.</p><p></p><p>\"I think quite rightly people feel: 'Hang on a minute, why did these police officers go into that meeting in his constituency office and then come out and basically say that he needed to resign and give an account of the meeting, which certainly doesn't seem to conform to what happened in the meeting?' I think it is perfectly legitimate for Andrew Mitchell to feel pretty sore about that.\"</p><p></p><p>The deputy prime minister, who was answering a question from a retired police officer who criticised politicians for denigrating the police, said that neither he nor Mitchell wanted to inflame relations with the police. But he said that Mitchell had been treated unfairly.</p><p></p><p>Clegg said: \"I don't think anybody wants – I am sure Andrew Mitchell doesn't want – this to descend into some long-standing slanging match between politicians and the police. That is a bad state of affairs. But on the facts of the case as revealed by the report from the Independent Police Complaints Commission it seems to be pretty clear that those three representatives of the Police Federation who went in to see Andrew Mitchell had every intention not to listen to what he said and every intention to go out and condemn him. Basic fairness says that is not right and it is correct that the IPCC has revealed that.</p><p></p><p>\"The IPCC report doesn't pull its punches. It says there are serious question marks about their honesty and their integrity. When the independent body that is there says there are questions about the integrity and honesty of police officers of course you should consider disciplinary action&nbsp;… Something clearly went wrong when these&nbsp;… representatives went into Andrew Mitchell's office with what appears to be only one intention in mind: to basically go out and tell the world's press that he needed to resign.\"</p><p></p><p>Clegg's remarks came after the IPCC indicated that three forces had watered down the conclusions of an investigation into the Police Federation meeting with Mitchell.</p><p></p><p>Hours after David Cameron said his former chief whip was owed an apology, it emerged that the IPCC's deputy chair, Deborah Glass, had written to confirm that an initial investigation had concluded that three officers from the federation who met Mitchell should face a misconduct hearing.</p><p></p><p>On Wednesday, 24 hours after the IPCC issued its report, Glass sent a letter to Ron Ball, the police and crime commissioner for Warwickshire, to clarify her position..</p><p></p><p>She said: \"We had no concerns about the quality of the investigation carried out by West Mercia police. It was the conclusion we disagreed with. In that regard, I note that in the first draft report submitted to the IPCC in July the senior investigating officer did in fact conclude that there was a case to answer for misconduct, although their final report, submitted in August, did not.\"</p><p></p><p>It is understood that the call for a misconduct hearing was dropped after more senior figures in the three forces said they disagreed with the initial findings of the West Mercia investigating officer. The Warwickshire, West Mercia and West Midlands police forces said that it had been decided that the three officers should not face misconduct proceedings.</p><p></p><p>Richard Ottaway, a Tory MP who is close to Mitchell, told Channel 4 News: \"[The chief constable of West Mercia] has got to explain exactly what has happened. If it is apparent that he has been a part of the change of the conclusions then frankly he has got to consider his position. If they [the West Midlands and Warwickshire chief constables] were part of it as well they are in the same position.\"</p><p></p><p>In a statement rejecting a disciplinary hearing, the three forces said on Tuesday: \"Despite a thorough investigation under the supervision of the IPCC we do not believe that there is sufficient evidence to support the view that the officers concerned should face misconduct proceedings.</p><p></p><p>\"Our view is that the officers have demonstrated poor judgment in arranging and attending the meeting in the first place. In light of this, our position is that management action is a proportionate response.\"</p><p></p><p>Glass had written to Ball after he criticised her report. He said: \"This is extremely disappointing. The officers concerned have not been given justice.\"</p><p></p><p>There was no response from the West Mercia force to the Glass letter on Wednesday.</p><p></p><p>The IPCC deputy chair wrote: \"While the circumstances of this case may have been unusual, it is not at all unusual for the IPCC to disagree with the findings of a supervised investigation. This is in fact explicitly provided for in the Police Reform Act, when a complainant can appeal to the IPCC against the outcome of a supervised investigation.\"</p><p></p><p>The row between the IPCC and the police and crime commissioner came after the prime minister said the conduct of the officers who met Mitchell had been unacceptable.</p><p></p><p>Cameron told MPs he supported Theresa May, who had said the police were \"quite wrong\" not to take disciplinary action.</p><p></p><p>He said: \"I agree 100% with what the home secretary said yesterday and I think we should be clear about what we are discussing here. The whole case about what happened outside 10 Downing Street, that's with the CPS and we have to leave that on one side until they make their decision.</p><p></p><p>\"What's being discussed here is the fact that … the former chief whip had a meeting with Police Federation officers in his committee where he gave a full account of what had happened, they left that meeting and claimed he had given them no account at all.</p><p></p><p>\"Fortunately this meeting was recorded so he has been able to prove that what he said was true and what the police officers said was untrue. He is owed an apology. The conduct of these officers was not acceptable. These things should be properly investigated, as the home secretary has said.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420239464|2013-10-17T14:03:15Z|ada9b63ef6bd487c263c974203489c8bea36881c -->",
