        "headline":"Body of missing Vittorio Missoni recovered from plane",
        "body":"<p>The bodies of Vittorio Missoni, the Italian fashion executive, and his fellow holiday-makers have been recovered from the aircraft in which they were flying when they went missing off the coast of Venezuela, according to media reports.</p><p>The remains of five people were found in the Islander aeroplane, which Missoni was flying from the resort islands of Los Roques to the Venezuelan capital of Caracas on 4 January, the Ansa news agency said, quoting local sources.</p><p>Those on board were named as Missoni, whose family own one of Italy's top fashion houses, his wife, Maurizia Castiglioni, and their friends, Guido Foresti and Elda Scalvenzi. A co-pilot was also discovered, the report said.</p><p>It said the bodies had been found with their seatbelts still fastened.</p><p>Missoni, who was 58, was the son of Ottavio Missoni, who started a small Italian knitwear shop in 1953 and turned it into a hugely successful name famed for its multicoloured zigzags and other striking patterns.</p><p>Ottavio Missoni <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2013/may/09/ottavio-missoni-dies-aged-92\" title=\"\">died in May</a>, aged 92, before his son's body was discovered.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420232537|2013-10-17T14:03:15Z|beb95809e5a3a49cbee4f1e830104ccf05e9369e -->",
