      "id":"world/2013/oct/17/china-corruption-crackdown-nanjing-mayor",
      "sectionId":"world",
      "sectionName":"World news",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T12:01:06Z",
      "webTitle":"China anti-corruption crackdown targets Nanjing mayor",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/17/china-corruption-crackdown-nanjing-mayor",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/2013/oct/17/china-corruption-crackdown-nanjing-mayor",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Ji Jianye under investigation for 'suspected severe violations of discipline and law', according to state media",
        "headline":"China anti-corruption crackdown targets Nanjing mayor",
        "body":"<p>China's corruption watchdog is investigating the mayor of Nanjing, it has announced, in one of the highest-level cases since the party's crackdown on official abuses began last autumn under the country's new leader, Xi Jinping.</p><p>According to state media, Ji Jianye is being investigated for \"severe violations of discipline and law\" – a euphemism for embezzlement, bribery and other official abuses.</p><p>Such announcements usually lead to charges, trials and convictions for senior officials, but the process can take months or years.</p><p>Although disgraced politburo member <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/22/china-move-on-bo-xilai\" title=\"\">Bo Xilai</a> and former minister of railways <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/08/liu-zhijun-sentenced-death-corruption\" title=\"\">Liu Zhijun</a> were convicted in recent trials, their cases began under the previous administration.</p><p>Ji became acting mayor of the prosperous eastern city in 2009, and was formally appointed the following year. He was previously mayor and party boss of Yangzhou, the hometown of former Chinese president Jiang Zemin.</p><p>The Central Commission for Discipline Inspection said only that he was under investigation, but the website of the People's Daily, the official party newspaper, drew links to Ji's oversight of mammoth infrastructure projects in the city and his connections to a detained construction tycoon. Nanjing media claimed that a sum of about 20m yuan (£2m) was involved in the case.</p><p>\"This is not a high-profile item on the Nanjing news websites and the announcement was terse. I suspect this is the beginning of a wider effort to look at Nanjing city government,\" said Russell Leigh Moses, an expert on Chinese politics and dean of the Beijing Centre for Chinese Studies.</p><p>\"Increasingly, central news coverage has taken a more jaundiced view of certain events in Nanjing and has been more critical of some circumstances there, particularly related to property and the economy.\"</p><p>The redevelopment of the city in the runup to next year's Youth Olympic Games has led to friction, with public protests when <a href=\"https://www.chinadialogue.net/article/show/single/en/4191-The-battle-for-Nanjing-s-trees\" title=\"\">trees were uprooted</a> due to subway construction.</p><p>Xi has pledged to root out corruption at all levels, in the latest of the party's repeated campaigns against the problem. High-profile recent cases include that of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/may/13/chinese-official-investigated-corruption\" title=\"\">Liu Tienan</a>, the deputy head of China's main economic planning body.</p><p>Most striking have been the investigations of numerous officials <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/04/xi-jinping-china-communist-leadership\" title=\"\">with ties to former domestic security chief Zhou Yongkang</a>, who retired from the politburo standing committee in the once-a-decade transition of power to a new generation of leaders.</p><p>They include Jiang Jiemin, the director of the State-Owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission. He was previously chairman of the China National Petroleum Corporation – formerly overseen by Zhou – where <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/28/business/global/china-expands-inquiry-on-graft-to-oil-executives.html\" title=\"\">four senior staff</a> are being investigated. Numerous officials and business people have been questioned or detained in Sichuan province, which Zhou ran for several years, including his former secretary.</p><p>The focus on the oil sector and Sichuan, and investigators' interest in the business activities of his son, Zhou Bin, have led to suggestions that Zhou is the ultimate target. That would be a bold move since senior party leaders have previously avoided targeting their peers or predecessors; sceptical political analysts say the inquiries may be intended to send a message to Zhou, others in his position and the oil industry, without further action being taken.</p><p>Critics of the overall anti-corruption drive say increased transparency and accountability are required to eradicate the problem and warn that individual cases often have as much to do with political manoeuvring as the egregiousness of an individual's offences.</p><p>\"Using legal means against political rivalries has become fashionable, especially with the anti-corruption campaign. If you want to get rid of a political competitor, people can use legal or disciplinary measures,\" said Bo Zhiyue, an expert on elite Chinese politics.</p><p>\"It's a very interesting political game going on. Everyone wants to claim some credit for the anti-corruption campaign; it's very much like in the 1950s when you had to find a rightist in your locality and there was even a quota system.</p><p>\"I don't think there's a quota system now, but different localities like to make some show of their efforts in the campaign. It will be a shame if they can't find any corrupt officials and will be to their credit to find someone relatively high-ranking.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420225333|2013-10-17T14:03:15Z|e62b55bd668059062367825c665d451dfe884d6f -->",
